04018nam a22005535i 9780520925922DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209259227 a10.1525/97805209259222doi  a(DE-B1597)520180  a(OCoLC)49570117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGN33b.E44 2001eb 7aSOC0110002bisacsh04a301/.012211 aEllingson, Ter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Myth of the Noble Savage /cTer Ellingson. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (467 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tI. THE BIRTH OF THE NOBLE SAVAGE -- tII. AMBIGUOUS NOBILITY: ETHNOGRAPHIC DISCOURSE ON "SAVAGES" FROM LESCARBOT TO ROUSSEAU -- tIII. DISCURSIVE OPPOSITIONS: THE "SAVAGE" AFTER ROUSSEAU -- tIV. THE RETURN OF THE NOBLE SAVAGE -- tV.THE NOBLE SAVAGE MEETS THE TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this important and original study, the myth of the Noble Savage is an altogether different myth from the one defended or debunked by others over the years. That the concept of the Noble Savage was first invented by Rousseau in the mid-eighteenth century in order to glorify the "natural" life is easily refuted. The myth that persists is that there was ever, at any time, widespread belief in the nobility of savages. The fact is, as Ter Ellingson shows, the humanist eighteenth century actually avoided the term because of its association with the feudalist-colonialist mentality that had spawned it 150 years earlier. The Noble Savage reappeared in the mid-nineteenth century, however, when the "myth" was deliberately used to fuel anthropology's oldest and most successful hoax. Ellingson's narrative follows the career of anthropologist John Crawfurd, whose political ambition and racist agenda were well served by his construction of what was manifestly a myth of savage nobility. Generations of anthropologists have accepted the existence of the myth as fact, and Ellingson makes clear the extent to which the misdirection implicit in this circumstance can enter into struggles over human rights and racial equality. His examination of the myth's influence in the late twentieth century, ranging from the World Wide Web to anthropological debates and political confrontations, rounds out this fascinating study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 0aNoble savage in literature. 0aNoble savage. 0aRacism in anthropologyxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520925922.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles